<section xml:id="section-variables">

    <title> Getting Started: Python Basics</title>

    <introduction>
      Did this work? In this section we will learn how to assign values to a variable in Python and display results. 

    </introduction>

    <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Create a variable in Python using <c>=</c>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Display a variable in Python using <c>print()</c>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </objectives>
        

        <p>
          A <term> variable </term> is like a container that can be used to store information or data. 
          In Python you assign a variable using <c> = </c>.            
          For example run the Python code below by clicking the <em> evaluate</em> button. 
        </p>

        <sage language='python'>
          <input>
            a = 2*3
            print(a)
          </input>
        </sage>

        <p>
          Note that the function <c>print()</c> was needed to display the value of the variable. 
          Now change the value of the variable <em>a</em> by adding 5 in the above code and see how the output changes.
        </p>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-more-variables">
          <title>More About Variables</title>
          <p>
           Variables can be named using letters, underscores, numbers, etc. 
            Just be sure to use the exact same name to call your variable. 
            For example, the following code has a syntax error. 
          </p>

          <p> !!!! Try to run the code as is and see what happens. </p>

          <sage language='python'>
            <input>
            Intro = "Hello again, world!"
            print(intro)
            </input>
         </sage>

          <p> Did you find the error? Edit the above code to fix the bug so the code runs correctly. </p>
        </subsection>

        <subsection>
          <title>Arithmetic in Python</title>
          <p>
            Python recognizes simple arithmetic symbols like <c>+ -, *, /</c>.  
          </p>

          <sage language='python'>
            <input>
              sum_and_product = (3+4+5)*2
              print(sum_and_product)

              nine_cubed = 9**3
              print(nine_cubed)
           </input>
          </sage>

          <p> Change the value of the variable to try out some basic calculations in the box below. 
            You can use the standard order of operations and parentheses (PEMDAS) for your input. 
          </p>

        <sage language='python'>
          <input>
            arithmetic = (9+3)/3
            print(arithmetic)
          </input>
        </sage>
      </subsection>

